	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#D6D1BE">	
		
	
			</font>
			<font face="Verdana" size="1"><b>
			<font color="black">--Submited by:&nbsp;
			<a href="mailto:mjacobs@jefnet.com">Anonymous</a></font> 
			<font color="black">On:&nbsp;11/01/1999 1:17:16 PM&nbsp;&nbsp;
			(<font color="blue"><B>List by:</font> <a href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/magic.asp?ID=5093&mode=details&spname=Cajoling+Whispers&pg=1&sortby=1">Front</a><font color="black">/</font><a href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/magic.asp?ID=5093&mode=details&spname=Cajoling+Whispers&pg=1&sortby=2">Back</a></B></a>)
			
			</font></b></font>
	
		</td>
		
	
	</tr>
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Also resisted less on higher level mobs (natch). One<BR>
of our more entertaining spells as it will easily charm<BR>
Hill giants and Seafuries and griffons, which can then<BR>
be used as makeshift pets to wreak general havoc on whatever<BR>
zone you're in.  Be very careful when using this solo as it's<BR>
of random duration and is a MEGAtaunt when it wears off (Hill<BR>
giants don't take kindly to getting charmed) and if you get<BR>
unlucky and roll a 10 second charm instead of the 90 second<BR>
variety you will have TWO very pissed off mobs on your butt :P <BR>
Best to stand just outside of range while your charmed pet <BR>
does its bashing so that if/when it breaks, you have time to<BR>
entrance or recharm quickly before dying.  Remember, using <BR>
this spell means no animated pet so if the charm breaks there<BR>
is nothing between you and that mob and it will not rest until <BR>
you're a greasy spot on the bottom of its shoe unless you can <BR>
recharm or entrance and memory wipe it.  If a charm breaks too <BR>
soon and I have time (jboots help here) I'll sometimes see which <BR>
mob was winning and charm that one the second time so I'm more likely<BR>
to have my &quot;pet&quot; win and share the exp.  Of course, all charms wear<BR>
off eventually and you have to deal with the po'd mob, but ideally<BR>
it's almost dead when it breaks.  Cast a quick tepid deeds or root <BR>
and a quick lower level nuke should finish it off. <BR>
<BR>
In groups have your tanks between you and the pet so they can attempt<BR>
to intercept and taunt when it breaks.  It may take several rounds for<BR>
them to get the former pet off you, but at least they should be able to <BR>
taunt the non-charmed one away.  <BR>
<BR>
Really talented enchanters can even solo mobs of three or more by <BR>
charming and using the pet to attack one mob while they themselves <BR>
root and nuke the third (or even entrance a fourth).  This is a little<BR>
like juggling knives - very impressive if done well, but very bloody<BR>
unless everything goes just right :)  Requires a very cool head and <BR>
fast and correct casting to keep all four knives in the air (or mobs off<BR>
of you as the cast may be).  <BR>
<BR>
All in all, a very fun and useful spell that is dangerous if <BR>
you don't know what you're doing.  
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
									
